Subject: New Circular 01/2022: GUIDELINES ON ESTABLISHMENT OF POST COVID-19 REVIVAL UNITS IN LICENSED BANKS

Dear Dilki Ishara,

A new circular has been published.

Summary:
Overview:
The Central Bank of Sri Lanka has issued guidelines for licensed banks to establish Post COVID-19 Revival Units to assist underperforming and non-performing borrowers affected by the pandemic. The purpose is to revive viable businesses and contribute to economic development.

Key Points:
- Licensed banks must formulate a revival and rehabilitation policy approved by the Board of Directors, including a mandate for establishment, scope of activities, revival mechanism, and other necessary measures.
- The Revival Unit shall be headed by a Key Management Personnel with sufficient authority and seniority, and licensed banks must ensure adequate staffing and resources for the Unit.
- Licensed banks may consider establishing Units at large branches or regional offices if they have more than 50 bank branches; otherwise, the Unit will be centrally located.
- The Revival Unit shall actively liaise with branches and other business units to identify borrowers requiring rehabilitation assistance and develop rehabilitation proposals.
- Licensed banks must not consider borrowers that have defaulted due to diversion of funds, mismanagement, or unviable projects for revival, unless they are classified as non-performing prior to 01 April 2020 or under litigation.
- The Revival Unit shall conduct awareness programs, provide credit counselling and business advisory services, and assist businesses in reaching out to potential investors.
- Licensed banks must adopt accounting treatment for facilities considered under the Unit as per Sri Lanka Accounting Standards and related Circulars/guidelines issued by CBSL.
- Licensed banks must report progress of rehabilitation proposals availing concessions under Post COVID-19 Revival Units to the bank's borrowers at the end of each quarter, within 15 working days.

Please acknowledge by 19 Jul 2026.

