A new circular has been published.

Summary:
Overview:
The Central Bank of Sri Lanka has issued a circular to provide concessions to affected borrowers due to extraordinary macroeconomic circumstances. Licensed banks are required to implement these concessions to help businesses and individuals recover from the impact of the crisis.
Key Points:
- Licensed banks must provide appropriate concessions for performing credit facilities of individuals or businesses whose income or business has been adversely affected by the current macroeconomic conditions, on a case-by-case basis, for a period of six months from the date of this Circular.
- Concessions may include a grace period for capital or interest, restructuring of credit facilities, or any other concession. The interest rate applicable for concessions granted to non-performing credit facilities shall not exceed 15.5%.
- Licensed banks must devise a suitable mechanism to structure the repayment plan for regular installment loans with an extended tenure, not exceeding the contracted instalment value of the existing credit facility.
- Borrowers who wish to fully settle any of the existing credit facilities without charging additional fees shall be given the opportunity to do so.
- Licensed banks must suspend recovery actions against all credit facilities that have been classified as non-performing on or after 01.01.2020, until 31.12.2022.
- Borrowers who are willing for an early settlement of credit facilities must make a request to the respective licensed bank on or before 30.09.2022.
- Licensed banks shall report the details of concessions availed by their borrowers to the Bank Supervision Department, as at each month end, within 15 working days, commencing from 31 July 2022.
- Borrowers who are willing for an early settlement of credit facilities must make a request to the respective licensed bank on or before 30.09.2022.
- Licensed banks shall not decline new loan applications from borrowers solely based on adverse CRIB records.

Please acknowledge by 19 Jul 2026.

----- EMAIL 2026-07-12T16:49:41.353368 -----
To: manager@bank.lk
Subject: New Circular 04/2018: Guidelines to Licensed Banks on the Adoption of Sri Lanka Accounting Standard – SLFRS 9: Financial Instruments

Dear Compliance Manager,

A new circular has been published.

Summary:
Overview:
This circular outlines guidelines for licensed banks in Sri Lanka to adopt the Sri Lanka Accounting Standard (SLFRS 9) on financial instruments. The aim is to establish consistent and prudent practices in credit risk management, impairment of financial assets, and regulatory reporting.
Key Points:
- Licensed banks must calculate expected credit losses for financial assets measured at amortised cost (AC), fair value through other comprehensive income (FVOCI), loan commitments, financial guarantee contracts, lease receivables, and contract assets within the scope of SLFRS 15: Revenue from Contracts with Customers.
- The aggregate amount of impairment allowances should be adequate and consistent with the objectives of the applicable Sri Lanka Accounting Standards. Licensed banks must have policies and procedures in place to validate models used to assess and measure expected credit losses.
- When calculating life-time expected losses, licensed banks shall use forecasts and projections published by CBSL, International Monetary Fund, and/or World Bank, unless credible alternative sources are available. A significant increase in credit risk is considered if one or more of the specified factors/conditions are met.
- Licensed banks must maintain standardised processes, detailed checklists, and decision trees to assess and identify SPPI features of their products and contracts. The role of internal audit shall independently evaluate the effectiveness of credit risk assessment, measurement systems, and processes.
- Licensed banks must submit all periodical information, including web-based statutory returns, to CBSL in accordance with existing Orders, Determinations, Directions, Guidelines, Circulars, and Instructions issued.

Please acknowledge by 19 Jul 2026.

